Expand: First, (x +3)(x -1) = x² -x +3x -3 = x² +2x -3. Multiply by (x -2): (x² +2x -3)(x -2) = x³ -2x² +2x² -4x -3x +6 = x³ -7x +6. Wait, coefficients here: a=0, b=-7, c=6. So (a,b)=(0,-7). Correct. For triplet {-1,-2,-3}: Polynomial is (x +1)(x +2)(x +3). Expand: First, (x +1)(x +2) = x² +3x +2. Multiply by (x +3): (x² +3x +2)(x +3) = x³ +3x² +3x² +9x +2x +6 = x³ +6x² +11x +6. Therefore, coefficients a=6, b=11, c=6. So (a,b)=(6,11). Correct. But in the case of triplet {-1,1,6}: Polynomial is (x +1)(x -1)(x -6). As before, expands to x³ -6x² -x +6. So coefficients a=-6, b=-1, c=6. Therefore, (a,b)=(-6,-1). But according to our earlier analysis, we didn't include this triplet in the four triplets. Wait, why? Because we considered the triplets with one negative and two positive, but here, the triplet has two negative and one positive. Wait, but the product is (-1)(1)(6)=-6. So this is a valid triplet.
